Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125}. Pop the tomatoes on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with
@oil{drizzle} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat. Halve, peel and
thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a
#garlic press{}). Cut the @halloumi{250%g} into three slices per person. Place the
halloumi slices in a #small bowl{} of cold water and leave to soak. Drain and rinse
the @lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large saucepan{} on medium heat and add the red onion. Season
with salt and cook, stirring occasionally, until really soft, ~{5-7%minutes}. Add the
@balsamic vinegar{12%ml}, pop a #lid{} on and turn the heat down to low. Cook until
caramelised, stirring occasionally, ~{3-4%minutes}. Once cooked, stir in the garlic and
cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @water{50%ml} and stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Bring to the boil
and simmer until reduced by half, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the lentils. Bring to the boil and
cook the lentils until piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste and add salt and pepper if you
feel it needs it.

While everything cooks, bake the tomatoes in your #oven{} until the tomatoes softened,
~{8-10%minutes}. Once cooked remove from the oven and set aside. Once the lentils are
piping hot, add in the @baby spinach{100%g} a handful at a time and cook until wilted,
~{1-2%minutes}. When wilted, pop a lid on and remove from the heat. Set aside.

While the spinach wilts, put a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add a drizzle of oil. Once
the oil is hot, lay in the halloumi slices. Fry until golden, ~{3-4%minutes} on each
side, then remove the pan from the heat.

Stir the tomatoes into the lentils, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.
Serve the lentils in #bowls{} with the halloumi slices and @croutons{1%small handful} on top.
Enjoy!

> The UK now eats more halloumi than anywhere else in the world, apart from Cyprus where it's made. We can see why! Everyone loves this 'squeaky cheese' with its delicious salty taste and firm texture. It's particularly good in today's recipe, paired with nutty lentils and sweet balsamic onions.